column1: #Text=Schreiber is a township of about 1100 people ( 2011 ) in Northern Ontario , near the northernmost point on Lake Superior and the main exposure of the Gunflint chert .
#Text=( Chert is a hard , dark , opaque rock composed of silica with a fine-grained texture .
#Text=It occurs as nodules ( flint ) or , less often , in massive beds . )
#Text=The town was named after Sir Collingwood Schreiber , a railway engineer , founding member of the Canadian Society of Civil Engineers , and deputy minister of Railways and Canals 1892-1905.
#Text=The town is near the main exposure of the Gunflint chert , which contains rare single-celled proterozoic fossils .
#Text=The settlement was founded in 1883 as a construction camp for the Canadian Pacific Railway ( CPR ) .

#Text=Steamships loaded with supplies for building the railway would dock at what was then known as " Isbester 's Landing " , named for railway contractor James Isbester , who in partnership with Robert Gillespie Reid was responsible for building many of the railway bridges along the north shore of Lake Superior .
#Text=Isbester 's Landing grew from construction camp to railway division point .
#Text=A station , roundhouse , car shops , icehouse and stock yard soon followed .
#Text=The CPR moved the divisional office from White River to Schreiber in 1912 , and thereafter remained as one of the town 's biggest employers .
#Text=The town 's economy is also sustained by a pulp mill in Terrace Bay , which is 15 minutes away .
#Text=During World War II , Schreiber was the site of one of the four work camps established for Japanese-Canadian internees .
#Text=Several Prisoner-of-War camps for Axis soldiers , sailors and air force personnel were also built nearby .
#Text=Many immigrants soon came to Schreiber with a large proportion finding jobs on the railroad .
#Text=A large percentage of these immigrants were from Italy .
#Text=Many others came from Poland , Finland , Scotland , Ireland , and other countries in Europe as well as other parts of Canada .
#Text=Highway 17 , the Trans-Canada Highway , runs through Schreiber .
#Text=Schreiber Rail Array Museum , 608 Winnipeg Street , ☏ +1807 824-2278 , ✉ schreiberrailwaymuseum@gmail.com .
#Text=A museum about trains that 's in a train .
#Text=It highlights the community ’s background as the oldest railway community on the north shore of Lake Superior .
#Text=It displays CP Rail antiques , documents and treasures .
#Text=Passing close to the town is the Casques Isles Trail , a scenic pathway along Lake Superior that forms part of the Voyageur Hiking Trail .
#Text=From the downtown area , pass through the CPR underpass and turn right immediately following the underpass .
#Text=Schreiber Channel One of North America ’s most diverse , best preserved and internationally known collections of micro-fossils within Precambrian rock is found in the Schreiber Channel .
#Text=This nature reserve is southwest of Schreiber .
#Text=Hike along the shore of Lake Superior and look for a group of unusual concentric rings embedded in the rock .
#Text=The rings vary in colour and size , with the largest more than three feet in diameter .
#Text=They are clearly visible over a couple hundred square yards of bedrock that slopes down to the lake .
#Text=Schreiber Beach provides access to Mount Gwynne through a rugged 2- to 4-hour hike that leads to a breath-taking 360 °view of the area .
#Text=Costa Foodateria , 402 Winnipeg St. M - F 9AM-6PM , Sa 9AM-5:30PM .
#Text=Fast food - burgers , fries , poutine , and " appetizers " - sold from a roadside chip wagon .
